## 📡 API Endpoints

All core application endpoints process input parameters using secure backend parameters, protecting the database layer from SQL injection artifacts.

### Authentication Scope (`app.routes`)

| Method | Path | Access | Description |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| `GET` / `POST` | `/register` | Public | Captures registration parameters, generates scrypt hashes, records new User rows. |
| `GET` / `POST` | `/login` | Public | Validates login parameters against recorded database hashes, opens active Session. |
| `GET` | `/logout` | Authenticated | Clears the state dictionary of the browser Session cookies completely. |
| `GET` / `POST` | `/forgot-password` | Public | Validates user email, mints random token, outputs link directly to system log. |
| `GET` / `POST` | `/reset-password/<token>` | Public | Validates time-restricted secure token parameter, overrides matching account password hash. |

### Storefront & Checkout Scope (`app.routes`)

| Method | Path | Access | Description |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| `GET` | `/` | Public | Pulls active inventory listings. Integrates case-insensitive parameters for live text filtering. |
| `GET` | `/cart` | Authenticated | Tallies current relational items stored in the user's cart cache. |
| `POST` | `/cart/add/<int:product_id>` | Authenticated | Ingests product IDs, appends item counts to the cart mapping structure. |
| `POST` | `/cart/remove/<int:cart_id>` | Authenticated | Purges target line items out of the active user's cart cache records. |
| `GET` | `/wallet` | Authenticated | Renders the virtual currency balance board and historical transaction paths. |
| `POST` | `/wallet/add` | Authenticated | Ingests hardcoded credit strings, safely wrapping amounts as high-precision Decimals. |
| `POST` | `/checkout` | Authenticated | Executes transaction isolation checks, records permanent invoice lines, clears cart data. |
| `GET` | `/orders` | Authenticated | Pulls historical checkout lines, sorting orders from newest to oldest. |

---

## 🔄 Core Workflows

### 1. The High-Integrity Checkout Lifecycle (Atomic ACID Step)

```
[User Clicks Checkout Form Button]
                │
                ▼
  Backend Opens Transaction Block (db.session.begin)
                │
                ▼
  Pessimistic Locking Query Executed
  -> SELECT wallet_balance FROM users WHERE id = :id FOR UPDATE;
  (Neon Database locks user's balance row against any parallel manipulation attempts)
                │
                ▼
  Check: Is user.wallet_balance >= cart_total?
                ├───[ NO ]──> db.session.rollback() -> Flash Insufficient Balance Alert
                │
                └───[ YES ]─> Execute State Updates:
                                1. Deduct exact Decimal cost from balance string
                                2. Create master Invoice row in 'orders' table
                                3. Migrate cached lines to permanent 'order_items' table
                                4. Record accounting trail row inside 'wallet_transactions'
                                5. Purge user lines out of 'cart' cache
                                │
                                ▼
                       db.session.commit()
                                │
                                ▼
             Flash Success Alert -> Send 302 Redirect to /orders

```

### 2. Password Recovery Mock Token Flow

Because sending real-world emails requires third-party configuration, ParodyMart safely replicates a secure infrastructure pipeline through server log routing:

1. User requests recovery at `/forgot-password` providing their username email.
2. The system executes an identifier lookup. If matching, it mints a URL-safe secure token string: `secrets.token_urlsafe(32)`.
3. The token binds directly to the model user record database field (`reset_token`).
4. Instead of sending an email, the backend prints the private endpoint directly into the deployment console logs:
`🔑 PASSWORD RESET SYSTEM SIMULATION: http://127.0.0.1:5000/reset-password/b_secureTokenString...`
5. Navigating to the generated URL validates the token parameters, allows inputting an override string, and resets the tracking field back to `None` for single-use protection.

